<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="vui-market-context">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>ux</group>
    <domain>ux-ui-designer</domain>
    <summary>Voice assistant adoption and platform landscape 2025-2026. Adoption stats vary by region; platform access is shrinking except for open ecosystems and custom LLM voice.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>voice-ui</tag>
      <tag>market-research</tag>
      <tag>platforms</tag>
      <tag>adoption</tag>
      <tag>voice-trends</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>beginner</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-29</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>VUI Market Context</title>
    <summary>Voice assistants are used by 8.4+ billion people globally; 62% of US adults use voice assistants; 71% prefer voice over typing. Five major platforms dominate (Alexa, Google Assistant, Siri, Bixby, custom LLM), but developer access is increasingly restricted except for Matter, Home Assistant, and custom LLM voice (Realtime API, Gemini Live, Pipecat).</summary>
    <why>
      <p>A product pitch or design strategy for voice requires grounding in adoption data, platform accessibility, and market trends. Stale or coarse numbers undermine credibility; numbers without attribution invite scrutiny.</p>
      <p>Developer access to voice platforms is shrinking. Alexa and Google Home are gated behind certification; Siri and Bixby are nearly closed ecosystems. Open alternatives (Home Assistant, Matter, custom LLM voice via Realtime API) are growing faster and deserve first consideration.</p>
      <p>Regional differences are large: adoption in CIS and LATAM differs from US/EU by 20+ points. A global strategy must segment by region.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Drafting a "voice strategy" section in a product spec or investor pitch deck.</item>
        <item>Picking a target voice platform (Alexa vs. Google Assistant vs. open ecosystem vs. custom LLM) for an MVP.</item>
        <item>Writing competitive landscape or TAM slides for a voice-feature business case.</item>
        <item>Briefing a new hire on the voice ecosystem and developer access status before they design or build.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Hands-on dialogue or interaction design — see core VUI design principles and conversation design methodologies instead.</item>
        <item>Privacy and security architecture — see the VUI privacy and security methodology.</item>
        <item>Pure technical evaluation of ASR/NLU vendors — use benchmark data and vendor comparisons, not market positioning.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="adoption-statistics">
      <title>Adoption Statistics (2025-2026)</title>
      <rule>
        <statement>Cite source and publication date in every numeric claim; voice market shifts >20% YoY in some segments.</statement>
        <rationale>Voice adoption numbers age in months, not years. Any deck citing 2024 data without a 2026 update is suspect.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Distinguish "users" / "active users" / "paying users" / "transactional users" — they are usually conflated in reports.</statement>
        <rationale>62% "use" voice ≠ 62% rely on it. Adoption stats are coarse and rarely segment by use intensity.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Attributed Adoption Claim">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[Statista (2025): 8.4+ billion voice assistants in use globally.
NN/g (2025): 71% of Internet users prefer voice over typing.
US adult adoption: 62% (NPR / Edison Research 2025).
Smart speaker households (US): 55% (2025).]]></code>
      </example>
      <example type="bad" title="Unattributed and Coarse Claims">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA["Industry says ~60% of people use voice" — no source, conflates active vs. transactional.
"Voice is the future" — no data.
Better: "Statista 2025: 62% of US adults use voice; NN/g finds 71% prefer voice for queries."]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="platform-landscape">
      <title>Voice Platforms and Developer Access</title>
      <rule>
        <statement>Weight developer access status higher than total install base when evaluating platforms. Closed ecosystems waste investment.</statement>
        <rationale>A platform with 100M users but gated developer access is less valuable than a smaller open platform where you control the voice experience.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Always include LLM-native voice as a separate row; treating Realtime API, Gemini Live, or Pipecat as "just another platform" understates disruption.</statement>
        <rationale>Custom LLM voice is reshaping the platform list faster than static stats can track. It deserves visibility in product decisions.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Platform Comparison Table 2026">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[| Platform | Ecosystem | Developer Access | Certification | Trend |
|----------|-----------|------------------|---------------|-------|
| Alexa | Amazon devices, smart home | ASK SDK | Human-gated, months | Shrinking |
| Google Assistant | Android, Nest, web | Actions on Google | Human-gated | Shrinking |
| Siri | Apple ecosystem | SiriKit | Heavily restricted | Closed |
| Bixby | Samsung devices | Bixby Studio | Restricted | Stagnant |
| Custom LLM (Realtime API, Gemini Live) | Any platform | REST API | None | Growing fast |
| Home Assistant | OSS, local + cloud | REST API, YAML | None | Growing |
| Matter | Smart home devices | chip-tool, APIs | Standards-based | Growing |]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="regional-variation">
      <title>Regional Differences and Disruptors</title>
      <rule>
        <statement>Segment adoption by region: US/EU, CIS, LATAM, APAC. Adoption in CIS and LATAM differs from US/EU by 20+ points.</statement>
        <rationale>A "global" voice strategy that ignores regional differences will underperform in key markets.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Disruptors to watch: LLM-native voice (Realtime API, Gemini Live, Pipecat), offline NLU, matter standardization, home assistant growth.</statement>
        <rationale>These four factors are shifting developer strategy faster than legacy platform adoption numbers change.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <title>Agentic Workflow</title>
      <p>Use Claude as a market-research synthesizer: feed the latest 3-5 reports (Statista, Voicebot, Gartner, Edison, NN/g) and produce a cited fact-sheet plus a platform-comparison table. A second pass cross-checks each claim against the source and flags unsupported numbers. Avoid "training-data" recall — always pull fresh URLs via WebFetch and cite.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Never accept a stat without a fetched URL and publication date. LLMs hallucinate market numbers fluently.</statement>
        <rationale>Knowledge cutoff bias drives agents to cite 2023-2024 stats unless freshness is forced. Always require grounding in fetched sources.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Flag and remove any extrapolations like "at this rate, 100% adoption by 2030." Remove them from the deck.</statement>
        <rationale>Trend extrapolation is a classic red flag for VCs and researchers. Stick to cited data only.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Human-in-loop checkpoint: any number entering an investor deck or contract must be reviewed by a researcher.</statement>
        <rationale>Numbers drive high-stakes decisions. Agent-generated claims without human review are liabilities.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="tools-and-services">
      <title>Tools and Services</title>
      <p>CLI tools for market research aggregation:</p>
      <commands>
        <command name="httpie / curl">Pull JSON from analytics APIs. httpie.io</command>
        <command name="pandoc">Convert market reports (PDF/HTML) to clean Markdown for analysis. pandoc.org</command>
        <command name="gh api">Pull voice-related repo trend data from GitHub. cli.github.com</command>
        <command name="npm-stat-cli">Track npm download trends for alexa-sdk, actions-on-google, pipecat-ai. github.com/anvaka/npm-stat</command>
      </commands>
      <p>Data sources:</p>
      <list>
        <item><term name="Statista">SaaS, REST API, paywalled but agent-driven pulls per metric.</term></item>
        <item><term name="Voicebot.ai">Industry analysis and reports; manual scrape is acceptable.</term></item>
        <item><term name="Gartner">License-gated research; not agent-accessible.</term></item>
        <item><term name="SimilarWeb API">Voice-app web traffic tracking where applicable.</term></item>
        <item><term name="Sensor Tower API">Mobile voice-app installs and rankings.</term></item>
        <item><term name="Crunchbase API">Funding signals for voice startups.</term></item>
        <item><term name="Google Trends (pytrends)">Free OSS wrapper for voice-feature interest signals.</term></item>
        <item><term name="NPR / Edison Research">Authoritative US smart speaker adoption reports.</term></item>
        <item><term name="Nielsen Norman Group">UX research and voice interaction trends.</term></item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="python-aggregator-stub">
      <title>Source Aggregator Stub (Python)</title>
      <code lang="python"><![CDATA[import json, re, sys, urllib.request
from datetime import datetime

CLAIMS = []
def fetch(url):
    req = urllib.request.Request(url, headers={"User-Agent": "research-agent"})
    return urllib.request.urlopen(req, timeout=20).read().decode("utf-8", "ignore")

def extract(url, html):
    pct = re.findall(r"(\d{1,3})\s*%[^.]{0,80}voice", html, re.I)
    bn = re.findall(r"(\d{1,3}(?:\.\d+)?)\s*billion[^.]{0,80}voice", html, re.I)
    for p in pct: CLAIMS.append({"src": url, "claim": f"{p}% voice", "type": "share"})
    for b in bn: CLAIMS.append({"src": url, "claim": f"{b}B voice", "type": "absolute"})

if __name__ == "__main__":
    for url in sys.argv[1:]:
        try: extract(url, fetch(url))
        except Exception as e: print(f"ERR {url}: {e}", file=sys.stderr)
    json.dump({"date": datetime.utcnow().isoformat(), "claims": CLAIMS}, sys.stdout, indent=2)]]></code>
    </section>
    <section name="best-practices">
      <title>Best Practices</title>
      <list>
        <item>Cite source and publication date in every numeric claim; voice market shifts >20% YoY in some segments.</item>
        <item>Distinguish "users" / "active users" / "paying users" / "transactional users" — usually conflated in reports.</item>
        <item>Show confidence: "Statista 2025: 62%" beats "industry says ~60%".</item>
        <item>For platform decision-making, weight developer access status higher than total install base — closed ecosystems waste investment.</item>
        <item>Always include LLM-native voice as a separate row; treating Realtime API as "just another platform" understates disruption.</item>
        <item>Segment adoption by region; avoid "global" claims that paper over 20+ point regional variation.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="ai-agent-gotchas">
      <title>AI-Agent Gotchas</title>
      <antipattern>
        <description>LLMs hallucinate market numbers fluently and confidently; agents cite stats without checking sources.</description>
        <reason>Knowledge cutoff bias drives agents to cite 2023-2024 stats. Always require grounding in fetched sources with dates.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Aggregator sites (Statista, eMarketer) quote each other in loops; agents cite secondary sources without tracing to primary surveys.</description>
        <reason>Secondary citations are unreliable chains. Trace to the primary survey (e.g., Edison Research, Statista's underlying methodology) before citing.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agents extrapolate trends ("at this rate, 100% by 2030") and include extrapolations in decks without flagging them as speculative.</description>
        <reason>Trend extrapolation is a classic red flag. Remove it or mark clearly as speculation, not data.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent-generated numbers enter investor decks or contracts without human researcher review.</description>
        <reason>Numbers drive high-stakes decisions. Agent output without human review is a liability.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Treating Siri and Bixby as "developer-accessible" platforms when in reality access is heavily gated and shrinking.</description>
        <reason>The platform table must reflect current developer reality, not past accessibility. Siri and Bixby are nearly closed.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
